{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507683"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:56:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:56:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2657"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2657"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.01,0.32,0.25,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112915"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94947"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112915"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe psychotic depression and nihilistic delusions that his chest is empty of organs. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears agitated with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable. An ECG demonstrates sinus tachycardia. Full blood count and biochemistry tests performed in the Emergency Department prior to admission two weeks ago were unremarkable. He is admitted to the psychiatric ward after appropriate investigations rule out any organic cause for his depression. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter a week of treatment with medication with inadequate response, the treating team decides that electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is indicated and this is approved by the mental health tribunal a week later. He has never had this treatment before.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is still required before he undergoes ECT?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI brain","CT chest","Serum electrolytes","Echocardiogram","Electroencephalography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is being prepared for electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) for severe psychotic depression. A comprehensive pre-ECT workup is essential to ensure patient safety and optimise treatment outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum electrolytes\u003C/strong\u003E are a crucial part of the pre-ECT workup and are still required in this case, despite having been checked upon admission two weeks ago. Electrolyte levels can fluctuate over time, especially in psychiatric inpatients who may have altered fluid intake or medication effects. Electrolyte imbalances can affect seizure quality and duration during ECT. Hyponatraemia, while potentially lowering seizure threshold (making it easier to induce a seizure), can lead to prolonged or poorly controlled seizures, increasing the risk of adverse cognitive effects. Hypokalaemia or hyperkalaemia can increase the risk of cardiac arrhythmias during the procedure. Therefore, checking electrolytes immediately before ECT (typically within 24-48 hours) is standard practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required before ECT. While neuroimaging is important to rule out space-occupying lesions or other pathologies that might contraindicate ECT, this would typically be done only if there was clinical suspicion, which there is not here in the presence of a normal motor and sensory examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely required before ECT. A chest X-ray may be considered if medically indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely performed before ECT. An ECG, which is part of the standard pre-ECT workup to exclude arrhythmias or abnormal heart rhythms, has already been done showing only sinus tachycardia. An echocardiogram would only be indicated if there were specific concerns about heart failure or other structural heart issues, which are not suggested in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalography\u003C/strong\u003E (EEG) is not a standard pre-ECT investigation. While EEG can be used to monitor seizure activity during ECT, it is not routinely performed before the procedure unless there are specific neurological concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to serum electrolytes, other essential components of a pre-ECT workup include a full psychiatric assessment, full blood count, ECG, and baseline cognitive testing. An anaesthetic assessment and medication review are also typically performed to ensure the safest possible ECT procedure. In this case, many of these investigations have already been done as part of the initial workup, but serum electrolytes need to be rechecked given the time elapsed since admission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Serum electrolytes must be checked before each electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) session to prevent potential complications such as arrhythmias or seizure threshold alterations.","A comprehensive pre-ECT workup includes psychiatric assessment, full blood count, electrolytes, ECG, and baseline cognitive testing.","Electrolyte abnormalities can affect seizure quality and duration during ECT, potentially reducing therapeutic efficacy or increasing adverse effects."],"references":["Lafferty JE, North CS, Spitznagel E, Isenberg K. Laboratory screening prior to ECT. J ECT. 2001;17(3):158-65. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11528304/","Electroconvulsive Therapy. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]. 2019. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etg","The Administration of Electroconvulsive Therapy. In: Queensland Health [online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0028/444763/guideline-administration-electroconvulsive-therapy.pdf","Weiss A, Hussain S, Ng B, Sarma S, Tiller J, Waite S, Loo C. Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Psychiatrists professional practice guidelines for the administration of electroconvulsive therapy. Australian \u0026 New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry. 2019 Jul;53(7):609-23.","Guidelines: ECT Minimum Standards of Practice in NSW. NSW Health. 2011. Available at: https://www1.health.nsw.gov.au/pds/ActivePDSDocuments/PD2011_003.pdf","A Guide to Electroconvulsive Therapy (ECT) for Consumers and Carers. Queensland Government. July 2022. Available at: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0027/726606/ect-guide-carers.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94947"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2657"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94947"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T03:21:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T03:22:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2657"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112915"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/188"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Psychotic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T14:32:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"g